snippet.textDisplay:
Im black and all ... but in terms of why rap isnt being considered Pop isnt a race thing (it may possibly be but i think i have reason to believe its not that). Its that most people dont want to consider rap 'music' ... it implies musicianship which most rappers are NOT musicians to the degree the word naturally implies. So its just this line that people dont want to cross because than itll make anyone think they ard a musician all they gotta do is go in a studio write lyrics and fill with a beat and a catchy tune and bam musician.

Because when you say music you think of more melody and instrumentation. Rap abuses beats and lyrics and hardly focuses on melodic composition. So its hard to say it rightfully should be pop or even considered music it barely qualifies although some songs do more than others ... even though id make a case modern day people listen more to rap than any other music genre. But its not something that id ever consider music because once you start considering rap music than that allows real musicianship to further get lost in the sands of time. Its how i see it. No ones gunna want to learn the notality of instruments and what it actually takes to make a good songs and to understand the sounds in pieces of music. People are gunna be lazy go into a studio with prerecorded sounds and beats and not know much of anything in terms of melody and all the music that will ever be made will start to basically be anti melody and just beat intensive and lyric intensive ... and thats not music. Its way more cadence with rap lyrics at that point. With a side of filler prerecorded sound cues. So yeah rap being considered pop music is a stretch even for me and i like rap. Sorry for those who wong agree or will take offense .... just know i dont mean to offend if you take it wrong still its honestly not that deep its just my perspective listen if you want.

snippet.textDisplay: Honestly he is right about "urban". 100% get that statement, But being a bit peeved about "rap"... I mean they had to fight to get rap in there to begin with. Maybe an argument for more R&B... but he doesn't really fit that 100% either. I understand wanting urban out of it, but being annoyed that he won in rap seems silly to me. You won an Emmy my dude, celebrate it.
